  padding-bottom: 80px;
}

════════════════════════════════════════════════════
RULES
════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. !important on background: transparent is justified
   here because Angular's view encapsulation adds
   component-scoped styles that can override normal
   cascade. The !important ensures transparency wins
   regardless of specificity.

2. Inter font on .persona-label-role instead of Syne —
   Inter is a condensed humanist sans that fits more
   characters in the same width. Syne is wide and
   decorative — wrong choice for a small circle label.

3. nameLengthClass on the role span uses [class]
   binding not [ngClass] to avoid conflicts with
   the base class name. The string includes the
   base class: 'persona-label-role ' + nameLengthClass

4. Ask CST fixed to bottom LEFT because the persona
   ring button is fixed to bottom RIGHT. Two fixed
   elements on the same side overlap each other.
   Left/right split keeps both always accessible.

5. The ::before overlay on persona page uses
   position: fixed so it covers the full viewport
   as user scrolls — not just the component height.
   position: absolute would only cover the component
   height and leave the bottom of long pages unshaded.

